ent to charity and especially informed by Augustine, synthesized Augustinian and Aristotelian elements to construct an ethics that does justice-in love-to insiders and outsiders alike. Decosimo offers the first analysis of Thomas on pagan virtue and a reinterpretation of Thomas's ethics while providing a model for our own efforts to articulate a truthful hospitality and do ethics in our pluralist, globalized world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aChristianity and other religions. 0aEthics. 0aVirtue. 4aAristotle. 4aAugustine. 4aThomas Aquinas. 4acharity. 4aethics. 4afinal end. 4ahabit. 4apagan virtue. 4atransformative synthesis. 4avirtue. 7aRELIGION / Theology.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311070398640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804791700zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804791700423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804791700.jpg  a978-3-11-070398-6  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles